'2022-04-07T17:24:39Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'The sample usage of `mongoimport` includes the flag `--writeConcern="{w:0}"`, but not in `mongorestore`.

> `mongoimport --host HOST:PORT -u USERNAME -p PASSWORD --db edx --collection importedQuery --ssl --type json --writeConcern="{w:0}" --file edx.json`

> `mongorestore --host HOST:PORT --authenticationDatabase admin -u USERNAME -p PASSWORD --db edx --collection importedQuery --ssl edx-dump/edx/query.bson`

It would be great to add the same to `mongorestore` for consistency and avoid confusion, since Cosmos DB always effectively uses a write concern of majority anyways. 

It would also be worthwhile to address the behavior discrepancies in different mongo tool versions.

## version
```bash
$ mongorestore --version

git version: d62df26a96814651d4e70c619b68a518dc6b048a
Go version: go1.16.7

   compiler: gc
```

'body': 'Provided cx with this doc (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/migrate-cosmosdb-data#pre-create-containers-with-enough-rus) for estimating needed RUs on their destination collection during migration and they came back with a question on how 2.4 mill RUs was determined which I am not able to understand/answer. If brought this up to my Team and they were also unsure on what formula was used:

"In the previous step. since the data size was estimated to be around 60 TB, a container of at least 2.4 M RUs is required to accommodate the entire dataset."

From my understanding, if looking at a storage perspective: estimated data size = 60TBs or 60,000GBs and each physical partition can hold 50GBs > 1200 physical partitions would be needed to accommodate all the data. I have been advised that while 10k RUs is the limit per physical partition, technically only about 6k RUs would be available. However, 1200 partitions * 6k RUs is 7.2 mill RU (and using 10k RUs limit would be 12 mill RUs) and not 2.4 mill RU.

if the doc could be updated with the formula used, it would be much appreciated

I also see why this is not deploying.

First the peculiar stuff:
1. The parameters are duplicated for the Cosmos DB account and database. Could probably simplify that to reduce confusion.
2. If you're not deploying multiples of the same resources at once, there is no need to load and read parameters from an array. In fact, I tend to avoid these because they tend to be different enough to make hard coding values less confusing to others.
3. The parameter name for the graph database is a bit obscure.
4. There are values in the json file for the graph which do not specify paths or throughput values are not really useful as parameters since they are almost never different than the default values. In fact, one of the values here was a source for one of the bugs with this file. There are even more examples of this for the Cosmos account.
5. The use of bounded staleness as a consistency model makes no sense, as well as the K&T values, given this is a single region account and even more so because this is a Gremlin account.
6. I don't see the need for separating the Cosmos DB account from the database and graph deployments. In fact, separating the account from the child resources may have led to the bug within your bicep.

Issues found:
1. The bicep file is missing the `dependsOn` array within the graph definition to the database resource. The error you're getting is because the graph was being created before the database was done being created. Generally speaking, I would keep all Cosmos resources for a workload in the same bicep file rather than splitting them up. This would have uncovered this bug sooner as your graph database would have failed for the same reason. But because these are in separate files, the Cosmos account was already provisioned.
2. This property was also incorrectly used. `automatic:gremlinGraph.autoIndex` This was set to false. This throws an error when indexing mode is consistent. Do not include this property when indexing mode is consistent or set to true, easier to simply omit.


Attached is the corrected bicep for the graph.

[cosmosgremlin_fixed.zip](https://github.com/Azure/bicep/files/8393692/cosmosgremlin_fixed.zip)

We have articles like this for our open source API's because there are very specific differences between these databases running as they often are on VM's versus a multi-tenant service such as Cosmos. These differences are both in compatibility with the underlying databases as well as other things that are less obvious.

For SQL API we assume that people understand this is a distributed NoSQL database. But for new users who do not understand the difference we have this article here to help explain why Cosmos is different. https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/relational-nosql", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/comments/1083642348/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

'body': 'The section on "Can I use multiple APIs to access my data?" is a bit unclear.

"Where multi-model means Azure Cosmos DB supports multiple APIs and multiple data models, different APIs use different data formats for storage and wire protocol. For example, SQL uses JSON, MongoDB uses BSON, Table uses EDM, Cassandra uses CQL, Gremlin uses JSON format. As a result, we recommend using the same API for all access to the data in a given account."

The above implies that I could create an account with the MongoDB API and access it using any of the other API's.

Is this really correct or do you have do use the MongoDB API only if the account was created selecting the MongoDB API?

'body': 'The section on "Can I use multiple APIs to access my data?" is a bit unclear.

"Where multi-model means Azure Cosmos DB supports multiple APIs and multiple data models, different APIs use different data formats for storage and wire protocol. For example, SQL uses JSON, MongoDB uses BSON, Table uses EDM, Cassandra uses CQL, Gremlin uses JSON format. As a result, we recommend using the same API for all access to the data in a given account."

The above implies that I could create an account with the MongoDB API and access it using any of the other API's.

Is this really correct or do you have do use the MongoDB API only if the account was created selecting the MongoDB API?

---

Interoperable, meaning you can access the data from both a SQL API and Gremlin endpoint simultaneously. 

To see this in action, create a Gremlin API account and navigate to the Cosmos DB Overview tab in Azure Portal. There you will observe both a SQL API endpoint as well as a Gremlin endpoint which can be connected to via one of the Cosmos DB SDK's and Gremlin client depending on which endpoint you want to connect to.

'body': 'The section on "Can I use multiple APIs to access my data?" is a bit unclear.

"Where multi-model means Azure Cosmos DB supports multiple APIs and multiple data models, different APIs use different data formats for storage and wire protocol. For example, SQL uses JSON, MongoDB uses BSON, Table uses EDM, Cassandra uses CQL, Gremlin uses JSON format. As a result, we recommend using the same API for all access to the data in a given account."

The above implies that I could create an account with the MongoDB API and access it using any of the other API's.

Is this really correct or do you have do use the MongoDB API only if the account was created selecting the MongoDB API?

All database and container resources can be migrated back and forth between standard to autoscale throughput, regardless of how they were created. 

However, throughput migration is a POST operation. ARM templates are idempotent and only support PUT. This means you cannot use an ARM template or Bicep, Terraform, etc. to migrate throughput.

To migrate database or container resources users have multiple options. Azure Portal, PowerShell, Azure CLI, Azure Management SDK or REST API.

Note that if a database or container's throughput is migrated from one throughput type to another, any ARM, Bicep, TF, etc. templates must be updated to reflect that resources' throughput type and value. You can refer to our [ARM Template Samples](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/sql/templates-samples-sql) for examples on how to provision standard and autoscale resources looking at the options for how these differ. You can also find PowerShell and Azure CLI samples in that same section that provide examples of managing throughput that include examples of how to migrate back and forth.

Thanks", 'reactions': {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/MicrosoftDocs/azure-docs/issues/comments/1058673748/reactions', 'total_count': 0, '+1': 0, '-1': 0, 'laugh': 0, 'hooray': 0, 'confused': 0, 'heart': 0, 'rocket': 0, 'eyes': 0}, 'performed_via_github_app': None}}

Here, it suggested that "single write region" is best high availability, but, the linked doc name is "configure your Azure Cosmos account with **multiple write-regions**".  Here, the "multiple write-regions" is confusing and inversed with the "single write region". 


If the best practice is that "a single write region and at least a second (read) region and enable Service-Managed failover.", from user perspective, may we want to see "How to configure second read region" and "how to enable Service-Managed failover"?

'body': " Patch operation is based on the [RFC spec](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6902#appendix-A.14). To escape a ~ character you need to add 0 or a 1 to the end. This isn't documented anywhere. The error thrown by the backend is a generic 400 with no information. 

Please add documentation and update the error from the service to explain it's a bad request because the path ended in a ~ that needs to be escaped.

- Options string of `Start-CosmosDbEmulator` is completely outdated (e.g. missing `-EnableMongoDb`)

spec](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc6902#appendix-A.14). To escape a ~ character you need to add 0 or a 1 to the end. This isn't documented anywhere. The error thrown by the backend is a generic 400 with no information. 

Please add documentation and update the error from the service to explain it's a bad request because the path ended in a ~ that needs to be escaped. 

Related issue: https://github.com/Azure/azure-cosmos-dotnet-v3/issues/2921

- Table under `Manage the emulator with command-line syntax` is outdated and missing the 4.0 option for `EnableMongoDbEndpoint`.
- Options string of `Start-CosmosDbEmulator` is completely outdated (e.g. missing `-EnableMongoDb`)
- `Start-CosmosDbEmulator` also seems to be missing the ability to actually accept values for the Mongo version, which means it always starts a Mongo 3.2 API with `-EnableMongoDb``

I'm trying to understand what is meant by the note in this documentation:

**"The  Azure Cosmos DB Java V4 SDK comes with the bulk executor library built-in to the SDK. [...] Azure Cosmos DB Java V4 SDK is the current recommended solution for Java bulk support."**

However there is no explanation of what this means in practice.  The code samples here don't work with V4 but if you go to the API docs for V4 of the SDK, there is no mention of bulk support or how it's implemented. Also, the V4 migration guide (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/sql/migrate-java-v4-sdk?tabs=java-v4-async) doesn't mention bulk support or how people using the older bulk executor library should migrate. There IS a link in that migration document referencing bulk operations - but it links back to this document which talks about needing to migrate to V4.

Could we update the migration docs to reference what people who are using the older bulk executor library need to do to take advantage of the "built in" support in v4?

We decided to adopt Mongo DB (Not cosmos with mongo api) simply because we never felt confident that our team will be able to write proper joins based on such vague documentation. After spending 10+ hours reading the concepts on joins and trying out the samples, I still have no clue how to write the JOIN to retrieve the data I want.

Some diagrams explaining how the joins work would have been of immense help. There are no other authors on the web who have taken a crack at explaining it because probably no one has understood the concepts. The entire explanation regarding tuples, and sets  is just not feasible.

Regards
Kunjal J. Desai

I completely agree with you that learning this flavor of SQL can be daunting at first. As someone with over 35 years of relational database experience, it took me quite a bit of time to become comfortable and competent in writing queries using our SQL dialect.

The reason most people struggle, especially those with years of experience in relational databases, is that Cosmos DB is a NoSQL database and stores data in a JSON format. Ansi-SQL and other relational SQL dialects are designed to work on tabular data. Since data in JSON format is stored as a document with hierarchies and embedded arrays, relational SQL is not suitable to use.

While I appreciate and empathize with your struggle to learn the concepts behind our SQL I do encourage you to work through the samples in our docs as well as these labs on Microsoft Learn [Execute queries in Azure Cosmos DB SQL API](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/learn/paths/execute-queries-azure-cosmos-db-sql-api/) and [Optimize query and operation performance in Azure Cosmos DB SQL API](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/learn/paths/optimize-query-performance-azure-cosmos-db-sql-api/). You can also go even further by finding json datasets on Kaggle and elsewhere and using Azure Data Factory to load them into Cosmos and experiment writing all sorts of queries.

Thank you again for your feedback.

I can certainly understand your confusion. Cosmos DB is a distributed NoSQL database that stores data as JSON documents. As such it must be able to work with data that can be stored in a hierarchy and/or as embedded arrays within a document. 

Standard ANSI SQL, designed to work with tabular data, is not suitable for this type of data. Cosmos DB provides a flavor of SQL that is designed to work with JSON data. As a result, there are some things which are different. But where we can, we try to frame things in ways a user of traditional relational databases can more easily understand them.

To your questions:

**Cross product** In the scenario described here the Families data has a document root aliased as "f" with an array of children, aliased as "c". The cross product is the joining of that root with each child in the array.

**f.NonExistent** This example query here is simply trying to illustrate a cross product result when joining on a property that does not exist in the Families dataset. I can see where this may cause some confusion. We will certainly look to make that a bit more clear.

**Families** is the dataset upon which all of these example queries are built. The article here provides a link to these which is just two documents in this article [here](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/sql/sql-query-getting-started#upload-sample-data). Apologies if you missed this.

Thanks for sharing your feedback.

'updated_at': '2022-02-18T02:24:48Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "It's commonplace for developers to use CosmosDB via Entity Framework Core, however as of late 2021 EF Core still does not support using CosmosDB's geospatial types as complex-value-types in EF entity classes:

* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/17317
* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/15896
* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/14336

And this is becoming a _gotcha_ for users unfamiliar with how EF works and that EF is fully separate from CosmosDB, for example: https://stackoverflow.com/q/60949543/159145

So a simple advisory in this article that makes it clear that using CosmosDB's own complex-types will not work when going through an ORM layer, like EF Core, instead of using CosmosDB's client lib/API directly.

'milestone': None, 'comments': 1, 'created_at': '2021-11-24T21:58:15Z', 'updated_at': '2022-02-18T01:16:29Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "It's commonplace for developers to use CosmosDB via Entity Framework Core, however as of late 2021 EF Core still does not support using CosmosDB's geospatial types as complex-value-types in EF entity classes:

* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/17317
* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/15896
* https://github.com/dotnet/efcore/issues/14336

And this is becoming a _gotcha_ for users unfamiliar with how EF works and that EF is fully separate from CosmosDB, for example: https://stackoverflow.com/q/60949543/159145

So a simple advisory in this article that makes it clear that using CosmosDB's own complex-types will not work when going through an ORM layer, like EF Core, instead of using CosmosDB's client lib/API directly.

'updated_at': '2022-02-17T20:01:25Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'I've recently implemented CosmosDB using Table API in to my website and am using the supplied SDK to generate Table Queries. The documentation here details that this SDK and API uses the OData standard. 

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/table/tutorial-query-table
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/storageservices/querying-tables-and-entities#supported-query-options

The documentation at the top here states "The Azure Cosmos DB Table API supports OData and LINQ queries against key/value (table) data."

This doesn't appear to be entirely true.

I have tried numerous ways to use the OData filter queries mentioned here:
https://www.odata.org/documentation/odata-version-2-0/uri-conventions/

But I'm unable to utilise 'startswith', 'contains', 'indexof' etc.

Here's what my C# code looks like:
```
            var query = ideaContext.CloudTable
                .CreateQuery<DataModel.Idea>()
                .Where(x => x.Username.Contains(username, StringComparison.InvariantCultureIgnoreCase))
                .Select(x => new DataModel.Idea() { Username = x.Username})
                .ToList();
```

I have also tried a number of other ways such as (including removing the space escapes):
```
            var filter = $"startswith(Username,%20'{username}')%20eq%20true";
            var query = new TableQuery<DataModel.Idea>().Where(filter);
            var results = await ideaContext.RetrieveByCustomQuery(query);
```

The result of which is an exception generated detailing:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1511516/135757730-c3598acb-dc1e-47d3-94db-f224ca71d46f.png)

Please can you advise on how I resolve this.

Thanks.

---

One thing you missed in our docs was the Note in our docs that you referred to earlier. I've put that here below and highlighted the relevant part.

So your observation is correct in that we do not support 'startswith', 'contains' or 'indexof'.

This is a known limitation among users and there is a [feature request for it](https://feedback.azure.com/d365community/idea/0376c31a-f66f-ec11-a81b-000d3a7cc2c1) on Azure Ideas site that you can go and vote up.

Again our apologies for the slow reply here. Hope this clears up the issue.

implemented CosmosDB using Table API in to my website and am using the supplied SDK to generate Table Queries. The documentation here details that this SDK and API uses the OData standard. 

https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/table/tutorial-query-table
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/rest/api/storageservices/querying-tables-and-entities#supported-query-options

The documentation at the top here states "The Azure Cosmos DB Table API supports OData and LINQ queries against key/value (table) data."

This doesn't appear to be entirely true.

I have tried numerous ways to use the OData filter queries mentioned here:
https://www.odata.org/documentation/odata-version-2-0/uri-conventions/

But I'm unable to utilise 'startswith', 'contains', 'indexof' etc.

Here's what my C# code looks like:
```
            var query = ideaContext.CloudTable
                .CreateQuery<DataModel.Idea>()
                .Where(x => x.Username.Contains(username, StringComparison.InvariantCultureIgnoreCase))
                .Select(x => new DataModel.Idea() { Username = x.Username})
                .ToList();
```

I have also tried a number of other ways such as (including removing the space escapes):
```
            var filter = $"startswith(Username,%20'{username}')%20eq%20true";
            var query = new TableQuery<DataModel.Idea>().Where(filter);
            var results = await ideaContext.RetrieveByCustomQuery(query);
```

The result of which is an exception generated detailing:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1511516/135757730-c3598acb-dc1e-47d3-94db-f224ca71d46f.png)

Please can you advise on how I resolve this.

Thanks.

Thanks for your question and apologies for the slow response.

The older Functions 2.x and 3.x extensions used our old .NET SDK v2 which used IReadOnlyList<Document> to deserialize items.

The newer Functions 4.x which are still in preview use our .NET SDK v3. With these you can deserialize directly to a typed POCO for example, IReadOnlyList<ToDoItem>. This is also the way it works when using the Change Feed Processor itself when using our .NET SDK v3 directly, rather than via Functions Triggers.

For more details on the new Functions 4.x please see [Azure Cosmos DB trigger for Azure Functions 2.x and higher](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-functions/functions-bindings-cosmosdb-v2-trigger?tabs=csharp)

Thanks again for your inquiry and again apologies for the slow response. If you have additional questions, please feel free to ask on our [Microsoft Q&A Forum](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/answers/topics/azure-cosmos-db.html)

'Hello.

"For example, suppose your max throughput is 20,000 RU/s and you have two partition key ranges, P_1 and P_2, each capable of scaling to 10,000 RU/s. In a given second, if P_1 has used 6000 RUs, and P_2 8000 RUs, the normalized utilization is MAX(6000 RU / 10,000 RU, 8000 RU / 10,000 RU) = 0.8."

The example quoted above is ambiguous since 10,000 RUs is also the maximum amount of RU/s of a physical partition regardless of whatever provisioned throughput is configured.
Therefore it becomes ambiguous if the "used RU" are normalized by the physical partition RU limit or the physical partition allocated RU.

As I now know this is normalized by the physical partition allocated RU so I would change the example to use other numbers that don't coincide with physical partition RU limit (e.g. 5,000 or 10,000).

"For example, suppose your max throughput is 20,000 RU/s and you have two partition key ranges, P_1 and P_2, each capable of scaling to 10,000 RU/s. In a given second, if P_1 has used 6000 RUs, and P_2 8000 RUs, the normalized utilization is MAX(6000 RU / 10,000 RU, 8000 RU / 10,000 RU) = 0.8."

The example quoted above is ambiguous since 10,000 RUs is also the maximum amount of RU/s of a physical partition regardless of whatever provisioned throughput is configured.
Therefore it becomes ambiguous if the "used RU" are normalized by the physical partition RU limit or the physical partition allocated RU.

As I now know this is normalized by the physical partition allocated RU so I would change the example to use other numbers that don't coincide with physical partition RU limit (e.g. 5,000 or 10,000).

> 400 RU/s for first 25 containers. Additional 100 RU/s for each container afterward.

In a later section about [Provisioned throughput](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/concepts-limits#provisioned-throughput-1), below _Per account limits_, there's this statement:

These instructions are not realistic for a reasonable sized database.  Even when maxing out the RU on my cosmos instance (10,000 RU), the `mongoimport` command errors out with a message stating "Failed: bulk write exception: Reason: (Response status code does not indicate success: TooManyRequests (429)" after uploading just 16 MB of records because mongoimport pushes the data over as fast as possible and with a fast internet connection exceeds even maximum RU cosmos settings.

this page there are two tables, talking about the same scenario, both called "What to expect during a region outage". In the first table about half way down the page, under the section "Availability Impact" for Multi-Region Writes it says "Possibility of temporary write availability loss, analogously to single write region with service-managed failover. "

Then in the second table called "What to expect during a Cosmos DB region outage" which is found towards the bottom of the page, under the heading "What to Expect" for Multi Region Writes it says "No read or write availability loss." - this seems to contradict the first table which says there may be write availability loss.

Could we clarify the content on this page.  Should we have two tables with the same title but different information on the same page?

Apologies for the extremely slow response here.

The reason why there is little to nothing in the way of showing JS/TS examples of using partition keys is that they are not supported for the Item class in that SDK, meaning you cannot do point operations for containers with 2+ logical partitions. They are support in the Items class so can be used for queries and doing bulk operations, etc.

This support has been on our backlog for some time. We are committed to adding it and hope to do so soon.

Thanks for your feedback. Will close this issue now.

throughput on shared throughput databases](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/concepts-limits#minimum-throughput-on-shared-throughput-database) there's this statement about minimum throughput as a function of the number of containers in the database:
> 400 RU/s for first 25 containers. Additional 100 RU/s for each container afterward.

In a later section about [Provisioned throughput](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/cosmos-db/concepts-limits#provisioned-throughput-1), below _Per account limits_, there's this statement:
> Maximum number of containers per database with shared throughput | 25

Are these two statement contradicting each other? Or am I missing something here? If the last statement is true, it makes no sense to include the first in the documentation.

These instructions are not realistic for a reasonable sized database.  Even when maxing out the RU on my cosmos instance (10,000 RU), the `mongoimport` command errors out with a message stating "Failed: bulk write exception: Reason: (Response status code does not indicate success: TooManyRequests (429)" after uploading just 16 MB of records because mongoimport pushes the data over as fast as possible and with a fast internet connection exceeds even maximum RU cosmos settings.

Thanks for providing your workaround. The key to your solution is the timeout 10.

As Cosmos DB is a multi-tenant service and resource governed, throughput is gated per second. In scenarios where users are doing very long bulk import operations, when using tools that do not have built in throttling, its necessary to do what you did in your example and amortize the loads over time.

We do have a server-side retries feature available now that can help with this as well but it will only retry over 60 seconds so for very long bulk import jobs it's not an option and people need to do what you did here.

Thanks again for your feedback and example.

None, 'body': '
When it says the following: 

> Clients can override the default consistency level that is set by the service. Consistency level can be set on a per request, which overrides the default consistency level set at the account level.

Our CosmsoDb is set to Session consistency. If we have a client make requests for strong consistency reads, is it exactly like converting the Db to strong consistency? For reads would there be any noticable difference?

---

It also can only be weakened. The overridden consistency is only noticed on the reads. It has no impact on writes.

To give you a specific example, assume default consistency is set to strong. User wants to be able to do reads but does not require or care about dirty or out of order reads so configures eventual consistency on the SDK client when instantiating it. Result is reads are single replica so cost 1/2 that of strong reads which are 2 replicas.

This page does not specify that each cosmos db account is for a single API only, and using multiple APIs means multiple accounts. It also doesn't say that multiple dbs in an API can be in one account. It's documentation that you have to piece together through a lot of reading and experimentation to determine. This ought to be explicitly stated.

There is no multi-model database I am aware of that does this. Additionally, most customers first experience starts by provisioning an account in the portal. The API type is a drop down and not a multi-select which should tip off most folks that they must make a choice.

In either case what you are asking for is indeed called out on that page in in this graphic on the same page as you filed this GitHub issue against.
